<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic demo user
    `x_casemgmt_demo_manager`. This is the first of the three demo personas
    created by the case-management POC scoped application; companions are
    `x_casemgmt_demo_agent` and `x_casemgmt_demo_viewer`.

    Persona role (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix and Section 0.5.5
    State-Machine Transition Map):
      This user is the HIGHEST-TIER operational demo persona. After the
      companion role-assignment row at
      ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
      grants this user the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager`, this user
      gets:
        - x_casemgmt_case        Create + Read All + Write All + Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_task   Create + Read All + Write All + Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_party  Create + Read All + Write All + Delete
      Unlike the case_agent persona, the manager's read/write scope is NOT
      restricted to "Assigned only" — the manager can read AND write every
      record in the three custom tables regardless of `assigned_agent`/
      `assigned_group`. Field-level ACLs on `assigned_group` and
      `assigned_agent` permit write access to this role.

      Special privilege (Resolved -> Closed): Per AAP Section 0.5.5
      State-Machine Transition Map, ONLY users holding the
      x_casemgmt_case_manager role may transition a case from Resolved to
      Closed. The role-check logic itself is NOT encoded in this user
      record; it lives in:
        1. ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml
           (Flow Designer subflow guarded by
           `gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')`)
        2. ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml
           (Before-update business rule that auto-sets
           `closed_date = gs.nowDateTime()` when the role check passes)
      This user merely has the role granted via the role assignment record.

    Validation Gate 2 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3 Workflow gate):
      The operator impersonates this user to perform the Resolved -> Closed
      transition on a case that already has all tasks closed (e.g., demo
      case 05 -> Closed). If this user is unable to close such a case, or
      if a non-manager were able to close one, Gate 2 fails.

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3 ACLs gate):
      The operator impersonates this user to verify the gate's pass row
      "case_manager has full access." If this user is denied any
      create/read/write/delete on any of the three custom tables, Gate 3
      fails. Full access is enforced at the ACL layer
      (../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_*_manager*.xml — Create/Read/Write/Delete
      ACLs exist for this role on every custom table); no client-side or
      business-rule guard is required to "grant" access.

    Why this user record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user` is a global OOB table (per the agent prompt and AAP
    Section 0.7.2 scope-namespace exclusivity):
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 2 (workflow:
      Resolved -> Closed transition demonstration), Gate 3 (ACL role-based
      access), and Gate 4 (portal submission as an unauthenticated
      requester routed to a queue visible to the demo agent). Tracking
      the demo personas inside the scoped Update Set ensures they import
      together with the rest of the application; the scope binding via
      <sys_scope> and <sys_package> source attribute groups them with the
      scoped app even though their parent table (sys_user) is global. No
      global-scope WRITES are performed: only INSERTS into sys_user (a
      data table) — the OOB sys_user dictionary, ACLs, and form layouts
      are never modified.

    Why this user is NOT a member of the demo group `x_casemgmt_demo_team`
    (per the agent prompt key insight #6):
      Only the demo AGENT is added to the demo group. The agent's
      read/write privileges are gated by "Assigned only" — i.e., the
      agent can only see cases where `assigned_agent = current user OR
      assigned_group contains current user`. The manager's role grants
      full create/read/write/delete across all three tables (no
      group-membership condition), so demo-team membership is irrelevant
      for the manager's privileges. Adding the manager to the demo group
      would be harmless but misleading — it would imply the manager's
      access is gated by group membership, which it is not.

    Why this user is NOT used as `assigned_agent` on any case or
    `assigned_to` on any task (per the agent prompt and the seed data):
      The case manager's operational role is to APPROVE / CLOSE cases
      (Resolved -> Closed transition), not to be the primary case worker.
      Per the seed-script's case table, `assigned_agent` is populated
      only with the demo AGENT, and `assigned_to` on every demo task is
      populated only with the demo AGENT. The manager is referenced only
      from:
        - the role-assignment record (granting case_manager role)
        - select Person-type demo party `person` references (per the
          seed-script's party table: case 03 Requester party, case 08
          Requester party)
      This separation reinforces the operational personas: agents work
      cases day-to-day; managers oversee and close.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — No PII:
        first_name = "Demo" (literal, not a real first name)
        last_name  = "Manager" (the role title as a synthetic surname —
                     unmistakably non-real; no real person's last name
                     would be "Manager")
        email      = "demo-manager@example.invalid" (the .invalid TLD is
                     reserved by RFC 2606 / BCP 32; never resolves to a
                     real domain — guarantees no accidental email leak)
        NO phone, NO mobile_phone, NO home_phone, NO business_phone,
        NO address fields, NO birthdate, NO SSN, NO photo,
        NO realistic full names, NO realistic email addresses.

      Rule 2 — No hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids:
        The user's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key, which
        is acceptable per AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to any other
        record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase hex value
        (MD5 of the canonical user_name "x_casemgmt_demo_manager") so the
        Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import,
        making the role-assignment and party `person` cross-references
        idempotent.
        The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> reference fields resolve by
        display_value/source attributes against the scoped application's
        sys_scope record (../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml) — NOT by
        hardcoded sys_id literals.
        NO <manager>, <department>, <location>, <company> reference
        fields are populated, so no other reference-resolution concerns
        arise.

      Rule 3 — No password:
        The <user_password/> element is empty (self-closing). A populated
        password (even hashed) in an Update Set XML would be an obvious
        credential leak risk. Demo users are signed in via the OOB
        `admin` impersonation feature in the PDI UI; they do NOT need a
        set password. To exercise this user's privileges in a fresh PDI,
        an operator with the `admin` role uses Settings -> Impersonate
        User -> select "Demo Manager" (display name).

      Rule 4 — Scope binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this user record to the scoped application
        whose sys_scope.source is `x_casemgmt` (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml). The display_value attribute
        is "Case Management" (matching the sys_app's short_description /
        the human-readable name of the application). The <sys_package>
        follows the same pattern with the source attribute pointing at
        the scope source name. This matches the convention used by
        every other scoped artifact in the Update Set (roles, ACLs,
        dictionary entries, choices, etc.).

      Rule 5 — Idempotency anchor:
        The user's idempotent key is <user_name> = "x_casemgmt_demo_manager".
        The companion seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        ensureUser() helper queries sys_user by user_name BEFORE
        inserting; the action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <sys_user> element ensures the same behavior at Update Set
        import time. This <user_name> value MUST EXACTLY match every
        downstream reference: the role assignment row at
        ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml,
        the seed script's DEMO.USERS.MANAGER constant, and any party
        `person` field on case 03 / case 08 Requester party rows.

      Rule 6 — No production data:
        No real first names, last names, email addresses, phone numbers,
        addresses, or any other personally identifiable information. The
        synthetic placeholder values (Demo, Manager, demo-manager@example
        .invalid) are unmistakably non-real.

      Rule 7 — Minimum field set:
        ONLY the minimum content fields required by the AAP template are
        populated: active, email, first_name, last_name, user_name,
        user_password (empty). All additional sys_user columns (manager,
        department, phone, mobile_phone, home_phone, business_phone,
        title, location, company, photo, time_zone, date_format,
        introduction, source, u_*) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (cmn_department, cmn_location, core_company),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user">
        Inner element: <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
        idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <active>true</active>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the sibling demo-user
        record at sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml, the role records
        in ../../roles/, and every other XML in the scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This user IS REFERENCED BY (these files resolve THIS user by
      <user_name> = "x_casemgmt_demo_manager", NOT by sys_id literal):
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
            grants this user the x_casemgmt_case_manager role
        - any Person-type demo party that uses this user as the `person`
          reference (per the seed-script's party table — case 03
          Requester party and case 08 Requester party in the canonical
          seed list)
        - ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js  (the DEMO.USERS.MANAGER
          constant equals this user_name)

      This user IS NOT referenced by:
        - any case's `assigned_agent` field (only x_casemgmt_demo_agent
          is assigned)
        - any task's `assigned_to` field (only x_casemgmt_demo_agent
          is assigned)
        - the demo group's sys_user_grmember membership row (the manager
          is intentionally NOT a member of x_casemgmt_demo_team)

      Update Set ordering (per AAP Section 0.5.2):
        - This record MUST be loaded AFTER the scope/app records under
          ../../app/ (since <sys_scope>/<sys_package> reference the
          scope's source).
        - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE:
            * the role assignment at ../role_assignments/
              sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml (resolves
              <user> by user_name lookup — needs this user to exist)
            * any Person-type demo party that references this user as
              `person` by user_name lookup (cases 03 and 08 Requester
              parties)

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as a List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles"). Semantic
        anchor only: ArkCase's role-name list pattern (where role names
        like "ROLE_ARKCASE_CASE_MANAGER" were held as plain strings) is
        replaced in the target by named scoped roles. This demo user is
        the principal that gets granted the x_casemgmt_case_manager role
        via the separate role-assignment record.
      - ArkCase's underlying `acm_user` table (defined by AcmUser.java,
        LDAP/AD-backed in production) is NOT replicated; the ServiceNow
        target uses fully synthetic in-platform users on the OOB
        sys_user table.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        mary|maria|@gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net).
      - No-extra-fields grep returns zero matches against (manager|
        department|phone|mobile_phone|home_phone|business_phone|title|
        location|company|photo|introduction|date_format|time_zone|
        source). Note: the ROLE NAME contains the word "manager" as a
        suffix, but the XML element <manager> (a sys_user reference
        column) is intentionally absent.
      - Empty-password grep returns zero matches against a populated
        user_password element of the form open-tag CHARS close-tag.
      - The user_name value matches downstream references exactly.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user">
    <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <email>demo-manager@example.invalid</email>
        <first_name>Demo</first_name>
        <last_name>Manager</last_name>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>ca171e30808ed474ab30ffb2d478a379</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_manager</sys_update_name>
        <user_name>x_casemgmt_demo_manager</user_name>
        <user_password/>
    </sys_user>
</record_update>
